namic features of modern capitalist life, such as rapid industrialization, working-class radicalism, dramatic population growth, poor quality housing, and regional administrative incoherence significantly influenced the Greater Berlin region. Examining materials on city planning, municipal administration, architecture, political economy, and jurisprudence, Urban Transformations recasts the history of German and European urbanization, as well as that of modernist architecture and city planning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCity planningzGermanyzBerlinxHistoryy19th century. 0aCity planningzGermanyzBerlinxHistoryy20th century. 0aUrbanizationzGermanyzBerlinxHistoryy19th century. 0aUrbanizationzGermanyzBerlinxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aBerlin.  aGerman architecture.  acity planning.  acorporatism.  ahistory of Berlin.  ahousing.  aindustrialization.  aliberalism.  apopulation growth.  aurban centres.  aurban planning.  aurban transformation.  aurbanization in Europe.  aworking class.  aworking-class radicalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262399640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442623996423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442623996.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles